{
  "doc_id": "24736",
  "text": "The ability to maintain postural control plays an important role in child development, representing a fundamental pre-requisite to competently perform skilled movements and complex motor skills [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Although the etiology of falls is complex, maturational and/or experiential immaturities in static (i.e., increased postural sway) and dynamic (i.e., gait disorders, such as a loss of symmetry or slowing of gait speed) postural control have been identified as important intrinsic factors increasing the risk of falling and sustaining an injury in children [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Therefore, an improved understanding of postural control is important for the identification of children with an increased risk of falling and the development of fall-prevention interventions.",
